    "subject": {
      "id": "RA_EN_006"
    },
    "input": "A 5-month-old girl presented with inadequate weight gain, poor feeding, vomiting, and diarrhea. She was born to first-degree cousins and had a history of sibling death. Laboratory tests revealed pancytopenia, necessitating transfusions, along with lymphopenia and hypogammaglobulinemia. Lymphocyte subset percentages were within normal limits. Serum vitamin B12 level was low (136 pg/mL), and serum homocysteine level was not measurable. CMV PCR test was positive. The patient received intravenous immunoglobulin, ganciclovir, and prophylactic antibacterial and antifungal treatments. Bone marrow aspiration indicated significant vacuolization in the myeloid lineage and notable megaloblastic changes. Molecular analysis did not confirm Pearson syndrome. The patient was administered intramuscular vitamin B12 and oral folic acid, resulting in clinical and hematological improvement. Following the discontinuation of vitamin B12 therapy by her family, she experienced a relapse with severe pancytopenia, leading to the resumption of vitamin B12 treatment.",
    "target": "Immunodeficiency by defective expression of MHC class II",
